I *think* I prefer the former of these suggestions since it is 
less markup heavy, but perhaps more clumsy.  
If we use it, we have to be clear what, for instance, 
`media="!tty,screen"' would mean.  I had considered suggesting 
something similar, but using a `nomedia' attribute.

An improvement on the latter might be to write something like

&lt;spanset&gt;
&lt;span media='tty'&gt;&lt;code&gt;r**2 = x**2 + y**2&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;m&gt;r^2 = x^2 + y^2&lt;/m&gt;
&lt;/spanset&gt;

the semantics being that if a matching span element can be found then
it should be used, otherwise the non-span content of the spanset should
be used.  This is a bit closer to the way HTML4 handles media types
in OBJECT elements.  It may however present more difficulties in the
implementation than simply requiring a (span +) content model?

Unless we're going to decide quickly on the second form, implementing
the first at the next convenient opportunity would seem like a good
idea, even if the second is to be adopted at a later date.

&gt; While we're on the subject, how about a &lt;div&gt; element, functioning just
&gt; like &lt;span&gt;, but at a higher level in the hierarchy, so that it can
&gt; include sections and/or paragraphs?

Yes it should be possible to allow media-conditional content selection
at any level (well, maybe excepting docinfo etc).  I don't suppose it's
possible to do this with a single element?  Using two elements to do 
this job does not seem to have any benefits for the author.

