<body>
The large majority of of Starlink documents which need to refer to 
routine elements 

(a) will have only a single codecollection element, and
(b) will use the name of the task/routine as the ID of the element in question 
    (i.e. you'll have something like &lt;routinename id='NDG_CREAT'&gt;NDG_CREAT&lt;/&gt;

At the moment to refer to something like this you have to write a 
reference which looks like

   &lt;coderef collection=allroutines id=NDG_CREAT&gt;NDG_CREAT&lt;/coderef&gt;

I propose that the `collection' attribute be IMPLIED and if absent
be taken to refer to a codecollection element with an absent `id' attribute.  
(An alternative, although I think it's probably not such a good one, 
would be making the collection attribute CURRENT).  

I propose also an attribute called `idtext' or some such, which indicates
that the content of the element is the same as the value of the id
attribute (or can you do some magic with CONREF attributes to take care
of this automatically?  I had to take my Goldfarb back to the library).

Taking these two together would allow the above element to be written 
instead:

   &lt;coderef id=NDG_CREAT idtext /&gt;

which is easier on the fingers and offers one less opportunity for a typo
in the name of the routine.

