On Fri, 16 Jun 2000, Mark Taylor wrote:

&gt; What's the reasoning behind having the content model for &lt;sect&gt; and
&gt; friends such that you can only have EITHER a &lt;routinelist&gt; OR other
&gt; text in the section?

There's nothing really deep here -- it's essentially for convenience
of implementation.

The processing of programcode documents turned out to be so different from
that of `ordinary' text, that it made their processing substantially
easier if I/we imposed this dichotomy.  It would be possible to make
this more general, but at the cost of some probably nasty rewriting.

&gt; If you just need to put text before the codecollection, which is 
&gt; probably usually the case, then you can do it within the routinelist 
&gt; element itself.

Indeed.  This does force you to have codecollections in
(sub)*sections by themselves.  Avoiding this would be a bit of a
programming nightmare.  It's probably good style anyway.

Norman

